name: 3,5-dinitro-N-(4-nitrobenzyl)benzamide
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1895
Reason: The target compound 3,5-dinitro-N-(4-nitrobenzyl)benzamide has multiple functional groups that affect its melting point. The basic unit we can consider is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C. Now, let's consider the effects of the substituents: 1) The amide group (-CONH-) is a strong hydrogen bond donor and acceptor, which typically increases the melting point significantly due to the intermolecular hydrogen bonding it can participate in. We can estimate this effect to be +80°C. 2) Nitro groups (-NO2) are also strong hydrogen bond acceptors and increase melting point. Each nitro group on the benzene ring can be estimated to increase the melting point by around +30 °C. Since we have three nitro groups, this accumulates to +90°C. 3) The benzyl group (C6H5CH2-) attached to the nitrogen of the amide group adds a large hydrophobic moiety, which can increase the melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions, estimated at +20 °C. Adding these adjustments to the base value of benzene, we can predict the melting point of the target compound.
Prediction: The benzene base unit starts at 5.5 °C. Adding the effects of the amide (+80 °C), three nitro groups (+90 °C), and the benzyl group (+20 °C), the predicted melting point is 5.5 + 80 + 90 + 20 = 195.5 °C.
